2026-05-31 | Sum of Consecutive Positive Numbers

	Question
Return true if n can be expressed as a sum of two or more consecutive positive numbers.
	Key Insight
A famous mathematical result:
		A positive integer can be represented
		as a sum of consecutive positive integers
		if and only if
		it is NOT a power of 2.
Examples:
		8 = 2³
		→ false
		16 = 2⁴
		→ false
		9
		→ not power of 2
		→ true
Why?
All powers of 2 have no odd divisor other than 1,
while every other positive integer can be expressed
as a sum of consecutive positive integers.
	Approach
1.	Check whether n is a power of 2.
2.	If n is a power of 2:
			return false
3.	Otherwise:
			return true
	Time Complexity
	O(1)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPossible(long long n) {
        return (n & (n - 1)) != 0;
    }
};
	Key Insight
A number can be written as a sum of two or more consecutive positive integers exactly when it is not a power of 2. Therefore, the entire problem reduces to a simple bit-manipulation check.
